<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Observer: Virtual reality
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It makes a refreshing change these days to learn that Treasury ministers are
not above poking fun at their own department, especially in the pre-Budget
period when they have traditionally been duty-bound by an official edict to
keep silent.
Thus Stephen Dorrell, Treasury financial secretary, took full advantage this
week of the change in rules which has eliminated 'purdah' ahead of the
November 30 Budget.
Dorrell, who joined the Treasury only 17 months ago after a two year stint
at the Department of Health with responsibilities including mental health,
told a London conference that he had been deemed well-suited to take the job
on the grounds that the Treasury contained the world's largest collection of
clever people doing stupid things.
</TEXT>
