<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For decades, the Lancaster look has dominated country house interiors, so
whatever you feel about gardening, it might be a pity to miss tonight's
programme in the series, An Englishwoman's Garden (BBC 2, 8.30). Nancy
Lancaster, aged 95, created a lovely garden just off the M40 outside Oxford.
Including her in this hotchpotch series was obviously a temptation even
though Lancaster was born in the US. However, she is still better known for
her influence on the British concept in the postwar era of what makes for
impeccable good taste .
East: South Africa, An Indian Experience (BBC 2, 8.00) is the second of two
interesting programmes about the Indian community in South Africa. There are
roughly one million Indians in the country, and many of them feel that with
the coming of black majority rule they are likely to find themselves sitting
ducks.
Otherwise, it is a dismal enough Friday night's viewing except for the
gentle nudge of nostalgia which That Was the Week That Was (BBC2, 11.15)
gives to viewers of the right vintage.
</TEXT>
