<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Blair pledges 'crusade' against
crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CRUSADE to free people from the fear of crime was promised by Mr Tony
Blair, shadow home secretary, in a determined attempt to establish Labour as
'the party of law and order' in Britain.
Mr Blair coupled a fierce condemnation of the failure of government policies
with a pledge that Labour would be 'tough on crime, and tough on the causes
of crime'.
He also attacked government proposals for replacing elected members of
police authorities with ministerial nominees, and the apparent intention to
amalgamate some of the smaller constabularies.
The next Labour government will introduce a wide-ranging package of
constitutional reforms, Mr Blair said.
He promised a freedom of information act, tighter control of donations to
political parties, abolition of the House of Lords, and the adoption of the
European Convention on Human Rights.
He also said Labour would establish Scottish and Welsh parliaments,
introduce proportional representation for the European parliament and hold a
referendum on the voting system for the House of Commons
'What we propose is a revolution in democratic accountability and control to
redistribute power from the government to the people,' Mr Blair said.
</TEXT>
