<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Full endorsement for ERM stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR will fight next year's elections to the European parliament on a
platform of support for economic integration and fixed exchange rates,
conference decided yesterday.
Delegates gave overwhelming support to a National Executive Committee policy
statement reaffirming Labour's faith in 'a co-ordinated strategy for
Europe-wide economic recovery.'
The statement confirms Labour's support for the exchange rate mechanism of
the European Monetary System, in spite of the collapse of the system earlier
this year.
It says that British re-entry 'will clearly require the adoption of policies
designed to strengthen our weakened industrial capacity and revive our
depressed economy'.
However, the statement does not set out a timetable for a British re-entry,
which the government has ruled out for the duration of the present
parliament.
The statement was strongly opposed by the leftwing Campaign group, which
described it as a capitulation to the 'strait-jacket of Euro-monetarism'.
Mr Tony Benn, MP for Chesterfield, dismissed the statement as 'the most
Euro-federalist document ever produced' by the Labour party.
The shadow cabinet said the statement would provide the basis for a Labour
landslide in the European elections in June.
Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, said the election offered 'an
excellent opportunity to take a crucial step towards getting the Tories
out'.
</TEXT>
