<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Beckett seeks to secure her job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS MARGARET Beckett insisted yesterday that her position as Labour's deputy
leader was secure, in spite of rising speculation that her failure to give
Mr John Smith whole-hearted support over the reform of Labour's union links
had put her post at risk.
Shadow cabinet colleagues - including Mr John Prescott who is now seen as
the frontrunner for deputy leader should he want the post - publicly
expressed support for her and paid tribute to her behind-the-scenes work.
Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury and a newly
elected member of Labour's ruling National Executive, said reports that Mrs
Beckett had equivocated had been 'blown up out of all proportion'.
In private, however, many senior figures were sharply critical of her lack
of enthusiasm for reforming the union role in candidate selection, and said
that her strongest card was that there was no desire within the party for an
internal election.
Friends of Mr Prescott yesterday said that he should be rewarded for his
effective and bravura performance in Thursday's debate on union links with a
senior economic position. A transfer from the transport to the employment
portfolio was seen as the most likely move.
The manoeuvrings in advance of the shadow cabinet elections took some of the
gloss off Mr Smith's narrow but decisive victory on the role of the unions.
The speculation has also intensified the pressure on Mrs Beckett to produce
an effective performance when she speaks to the conference today on party
campaigns.
In a series of media interviews yesterday Mrs Beckett said that her position
was safe and that although she agreed Mr Prescott would be a 'superb' deputy
leader, 'I'm afraid I do think that I'd be a better one'.
She said she did not accept that she gave 'only qualified support' to Mr
Smith.
'It is nonsense for people to try to pretend there are some differences
between me and John or that it has caused problems for us and the party,'
she said.
Her comments, however, failed to put an end to discussion about her
continued future at a senior level. Some colleagues said that her task is
now to ensure that if anyone outside the shadow cabinet - such as Mr Bryan
Gould - sought to mount a challenge, he would not achieve support to force a
contest.
The prospects of a reshuffle after the shadow cabinet elections later this
month has prompted some frontbenchers to talk about a move from education
for Mrs Ann Taylor, whom many colleagues think is ineffective in the job.
</TEXT>
<XX>
