<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / European works council marks Ford policy shift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A EUROPEAN works council is to be established at the Ford motor company
covering its 100,000 employees in Britain, Germany, Portugal, Spain and
Belgium.
Mr Tony Woodley, TGWU general union national officer for the car industry in
Britain yesterday said: 'Ford workers throughout Europe can today celebrate
a new European unity among their unions.
'We recognise Ford operates as one European entity in the single market.
Unfortunately the backward British government has singularly failed to come
to terms with its social obligations towards workers in the European
community.'
Until now, Ford has opposed the idea of a works council covering all its
European operations. But the EC is soon expected to endorse a directive on
works councils that will compel Ford and other companies to introduce them.
The new body will contain full-time union officials and plant conveners from
the UK. German members will come from existing works councils in Ford
plants.
It has taken long discussions between the unions to reach agreement on the
Ford works council.
There are around 25 European-wide company works councils, mainly in
French-owned enterprises and other car companies.
Separately, the final touches are being put to a union pay claim at Ford in
the UK. Conscious of the troubles facing the company, union negotiators
intend to give their highest priority to job security rather than a big pay
rise.
Vauxhall faces industrial conflict if it fails to improve its existing
two-year wage offer to its 8,000 workers when it meets union officials next
Wednesday.
Mr Roger Butler, the AEEU engineering union's chief negotiator, said unions
would hold a strike ballot if the offer of a 2.1 per cent rise this year and
2.6 per cent next year is not increased.
The unions are seeking a substantial rise and a cut in working hours. They
say productivity has improved by 8 per cent over the past 12 months and the
company is making substantial profits.
</TEXT>
