<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Whitehall productivity 'lagging'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CIVIL Service has lagged behind the private sector in increasing the
productivity of its staff, according to a report published today by the
European Policy Forum, the independent think tank.
Between 1987 and 1993, the number of civil servants fell 7.3 per cent from
597,814 to 554,212, according to the most recent government figures.
The Forum contrasts these figures with productivity increases at the banks,
which it says are similar, people-intensive administrative organisations.
They have cut their staff numbers by more than 16 per cent in the past four
years.
The report will add to pressure on the government to curb Civil Service
staff as part of a drive to reduce public expenditure rather than increase
taxes.
Much of the reduction in civil service numbers has been achieved by
reclassifying civil servants to take them out of the figures, the Forum
says.
Examples include the transfer of 3,300 staff from the Department of Health
special hospitals to a special health authority in 1990. The introduction of
commercial management in the Rosyth and Devonport dockyards took out another
16,600.
Excluding such changes, numbers have fallen by just 17,382 since 1987, a
fall of 3.9 per cent. This contrasts with the big four banks which have cut
44,940 staff since 1989, a drop of 16 per cent.
The report says that similar staffing reductions in the Civil Service could
cut over 60,000 jobs, a 10 per cent reduction. It calls on ministers to set
targets for 'downsizing' on this scale over the next four years.
The Forum says that the failure to squeeze down numbers in many government
departments has added to public expenditure and reduced the scope for
improving the quality of services.
Civil Service Numbers. European Policy Forum, 20 Queen Anne's Gate, London
SW1H 9AA. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
