<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Pay rises faster in public sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAY IN the public sector rose faster than in the private sector for the
third year running in the year to April, according to the government's New
Earnings Survey figures for this year published yesterday.
The figures show a 4.3 per cent increase for the public sector compared with
4 per cent for the private sector. That is in spite of the fact that many
key public-sector groups had been affected by the government's 1.5 per cent
pay limit when the survey data was compiled.
Public-sector pay experts, such as Mr Chris Trinder of the Public Finance
Foundation, said the figures helped to explain why the government has
imposed another limit on public-sector pay next year. The figures also show
that public-sector pay is drifting well over official ceilings.
Mr Trinder said: 'The decentralisation of pay in the public sector may have
given flexibility advantages, but at a price.'
Taking the three years to April this year, pay in the public sector has
increased by 25.2 per cent compared with 18.6 per cent in the private
sector. Inflation was 12.4 per cent over the period. Over the same period,
the economy contracted by 2 per cent.
The public sector was also much more generous to the low-paid, with the
lowest 10 per cent receiving 4.8 per cent compared with 3.5 per cent for the
lowest-paid 10 per cent in the private sector.
Although women's pay rose slightly faster than men's at 4.8 per cent, the
biggest reductions in pay were for full-time non-manual women workers under
18, whose pay fell 9.3 per cent. This may reflect the lagged effect of the
abolition of wages councils for young people.
However, those workers who are still covered by wages councils saw their pay
rise 4.8 per cent, considerably above the average in the private sector.
Overall earnings inequality grew, with weekly manual earnings rising only
2.5 per cent to Pounds 257 compared with non-manual occupations which rose
4.4 per cent to Pounds 350. The average for women at Pounds 253 was just
over 71 per cent of the male figure of Pounds 354. That rises to 79 per cent
if overtime is excluded.
Greater London continued to see earnings increases higher than in other
parts of the country at 5.9 per cent - making an average of Pounds 408. The
lowest increases were in East Anglia at 1.3 per cent and Tyne and Wear's 1.7
per cent.
Average pay for managers and administrators was Pounds 460, a rise of 6.2
per cent, with average professional pay at Pounds 444, a rise of 5.7 per
cent.
New Earnings Survey 1993, Part A. HMSO. Pounds 12.50
 -------------------------------------------------------------
                         GROSS WEEKLY PAY
 -------------------------------------------------------------
                                       Pounds      % rise**
 -------------------------------------------------------------
Company treasurers                     745.6          7.1
Accountants                            473.1          6.4
Civil Service executive officers         315          5.2
Production managers                    462.8          4.9
University teachers                    525.9          4.3
Marketing and sales managers           515.1          2.5
Solicitors                             559.8          0.3
 -------------------------------------------------------------
