<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Goode report strikes a fine balance: Pensions industry
believes interests of both employers and members have been recognised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PENSIONS industry has given a broad welcome to the Goode Committee
report, saying it preserves employers' rights to abandon unaffordable
pension promises for the future while ensuring that past promises are kept.
'Our overall reaction is that it has struck a good balance between the
interests of employers and that of scheme members,' said Mr Ron Amy,
chairman of the National Association of Pension Funds and benefits manager
at Grand Metropolitan.
'However, there were a couple of areas in which we felt it could have gone
further,' he said.
The association would have liked to see mandatory training requirements for
all trustees, especially since the new regime will give them greater
responsibilities.
It regretted there was no specific requirement that assets be placed with a
custodian. A number of schemes still act as their own custodian.
The actuarial profession, while broadly welcoming the recommendations for
protecting pensioners, has sounded alarm bells about a proposal for minimum
solvency standards.
Mr Roger Key, partner at R. Watsons and Sons, consulting actuaries, said
there was a risk that the equities market would plummet because of the way
the minimum solvency requirement would be calculated.
The report recommends that actuaries calculate the so-called cash equivalent
value of the transfer value of each member, assuming the scheme were to be
wound up immediately. The sum is intended to represent the amount the member
would need to purchase equivalent benefits in the market although it does
not take account of actual market prices for annuities at any particular
time.
The actuarial profession now calculates these with reference to yields on UK
government gilts, and assumes that the rate of return the member will earn
on his investment is equal to those. However, more than 80 per cent of the
average UK pension scheme is invested in equities, most of that in the UK.
Mr Key said a sudden crash in the value of the UK equities market could
leave a scheme that met the 100 per cent solvency standard on one day very
far below that a few days later. Thus, for safety's sake, many actuaries are
likely to recommend that schemes switch their investments to gilts which
historically have yielded less than equities.
That could make pension schemes more expensive to finance, he said, and
discourage employers from providing defined benefit final salary schemes.
Mr Bill Rayner, senior actuary at consultants William M. Mercer, said that
while the effects on equity values could be dire, the profession had begun
to address the matter.
The Goode report directs the actuarial profession to consider ways of
narrowing the diverse methods used to calculate transfer values within the
industry.
In July, the Pensions Committee of the Faculty and Institute of Actuaries
began looking at calculation methods including whether some account should
be taken of equities.
</TEXT>
