<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Rivers could run orange with pollution: A hazardous
side-effect of mine closures is rising water tables
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GEOLOGISTS, engineers and planners met in Durham yesterday to discuss a
potentially dangerous side-effect of pit closures - the threat of water
rising through abandoned mines to pollute rivers, killing wildlife and
contaminating drinking water.
Britain's recent wave of coal-mine closures and the proposed privatisation
of remaining British Coal assets is focusing attention on what is to happen
to its costly pumping activities.
The implications are serious for many coalfield areas of England and Wales,
but have struck first in County Durham which, after centuries of intensive
mining, has suddenly found itself without a single deep pit.
At present, a network of 11 pumping stations pumps 25m gallons of water
every day into the River Wear from below the warren of mineworkings. British
Coal has until now met the costs of up to Pounds 6m a year to keep dry its
remaining Durham coastal pits.
But it now has no operational interest in continuing the Durham pumping, as
the coalfield's only surviving pit, Wearmouth, in Tyne and Wear, does not
depend on it.
British Coal and the National Rivers Authority, the river pollution
watchdog, have been in negotiation for the past year over the issue.
British Coal is obliged to give the watchdog 14 days notice if it intends to
cease pumping. But the watchdog is considering legal action against British
Coal.
It is unclear whether legal action - possibly an injunction - could succeed.
Under the 1989 Water Act, permitting water to flow from abandoned mines is
not an offence, although causing it to do so is.
If the County Durham pumping ceased, the water table would rise into the old
mineworkings, and could become contaminated with sulphuric acid, iron,
manganese, aluminium and sulphates, which could then be discharged into
rivers.
The reality was demonstrated last year when 80m gallons of water from the
abandoned Cornish tin mine Wheal Jane polluted the River Carnon.
A recent study by the watchdog's consultants Wardell Armstrong concluded
that discharges of polluted minewater into the River Wear, initially around
Bishop Auckland, would begin three months after pumping stopped.
Stretches of the Wear could be affected by ochrous depots of iron compounds.
This could damage fish and river life and turn the water a vivid orange.
'Imagine an orange necklace around the peninsula of Durham Cathedral,' says
deputy county council leader Mr Bob Pendlebury, who chaired yesterday's
seminar.
The council also fears landslides and subsidence, due to waterlogging of
soils as the water table rises.
The delegates at yesterday's seminar agreed that action is required:
To ensure pumping continues until a solution to minewater pollution is
found. To press for a national working party, including government
departments, British Coal and the watchdog.
To provide the resources needed to assess environmental damage and potential
pollution and subsidence.
To seek legislation on environmental safeguards on abandoned mine workings.
North East Water, which supplies 150,000 customers from its Lumley works
near the Wear in Chester-le-Street has warned that, if pumping ends,
minewater pollution could force it to develop new treatment facilities on
the Tyne, costing Pounds 25m.
Government proposals on British Coal's pumping activities are not due until
November, when the privatisation bill is made public.
</TEXT>
