FT  01 OCT 93 / Wandsworth plans grammar schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS to convert a compre-hensive school into a selective grammar school
have been announced by the south London borough of Wandsworth, the
Conservative 'flagship' authority.
The boys-only Ernest Bevin School is asking to select 90 of its annual
intake of 180 on academic criteria. For equal-opportunities reasons,
Wandsworth is asking the neighbouring girls' school, Burnt-wood, which has
opted out of local-authority control, to make a similar number of places
selective.
If Burntwood does not agree, Wandsworth plans to open a new girls' grammar
school.
Mr Tony Belton, leader of the Labour group, vowed to oppose the proposals.
