<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Polly Peck charges dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office yesterday effectively ended its Polly Peck
prosecutions when it dropped all charges against Mr John Turner, the
company's former group accountant originally due to stand trial alongside Mr
Asil Nadir, the fugitive businessman.
The criminal proceedings against Mr Nadir remain active and the SFO
yesterday insisted it would bring the Polly Peck chairman to trial if he
could be brought back from northern Cyprus where he fled in May to avoid
prosecution.
Efforts, including diplomatic moves, are still being made by the government
to ensure Mr Nadir's return. However, the central problem - the lack of an
extradition agreement between northern Cyprus and the UK - remains.
Investigators close to the case concede that the chances of Mr Nadir
returning to stand trial in the foreseeable future must now be regarded as
remote.
Mr Asil Nadir, speaking from his home in northern Cyprus yesterday, said he
was delighted the charges against Mr Turner had been dropped: 'It's great
news. Let's hope my case will also be dropped.'
The trial of both Mr Turner, who faced two charges of false accounting, and
Mr Nadir, who faced 13 charges of theft involving Pounds 34m, had been due
to begin on Monday at the Old Bailey. However, Mr Robert Owen QC, for the
SFO, told the court yesterday that there was 'little prospect' of Mr Nadir
returning to the UK by then.
He said that the SFO's case had been that Mr Turner had made accounting
entries to conceal the thefts carried out by Mr Nadir. Mr Turner's defence
would be seriously prejudiced if he were tried before a jury had brought in
a verdict on the alleged thefts by the Polly Peck chairman. There was also a
conflict in the evidence due to be given by Mr Nadir and Mr Turner over the
accounting entries.
It would be 'manifestly unjust' to postpone proceedings against Mr Turner
indefinitely while waiting for Mr Nadir to return to face trial.
Mr Turner, who had always denied the charges, was formally acquitted by the
judge and had costs awarded in his favour. Mr Turner said he he was 'clearly
pleased' with his acquittal.
</TEXT>
