<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / No change to court dress
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER a year-long consulta-tion exercise, Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor
(above), yesterday announced that there would be no change in court dress,
Robert Rice writes.
Barristers will continue to wear wigs and gowns in court. High Court judges
will retain their ceremonial full-bottomed wigs, knee breeches, hose and
buckled shoes, beneath a scarlet cloth and fur mantle.
Responses from jurors, witnesses, the public, the legal profession and the
judiciary overwhelmingly backed the status quo. The majority felt that the
formal dress had a significant role to play in maintaining respect for the
authority and status of the court.
More than 500 responses were received from organisations and individuals.
Only 15 per cent of all respondents favoured abolition of daily court dress,
67 per cent favoured the status quo and the remainder favoured
simplification, such as abolishing the use of wigs.
Ceremonial court dress attracted comment from only 20 per cent of
respondents, of whom a fifth favoured its abolition.
</TEXT>
