<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Recall for defective Lucozade bottles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMITHKLINE Beecham yester-day ordered the recall of 12m glass bottles of its
Lucozade soft drink after discovering a defect which caused the neck on some
of them to crack when opened.
The company said it had learned of the problem from Rockware, the
manufacturer, late on Monday. It said the problems affected 'only a very
small number' of bottles.
It has immediately stopped production and launched an investigation to
identify how many bottles had reached the market. It has asked retailers to
remove affected stock from their shelves and has set up a free telephone
helpline - 0800-318-066.
Production remained suspended while SmithKline Beecham and Rockware worked
to correct the defect. SmithKline Beecham could not estimate the cost of the
recall and loss of output, but said it would not have a material impact on
its financial position.
The recall covers 250ml and 300ml bottles containing original Lucozade and
orange barley, lemon barley and tropical barley flavours. No other products
in the Lucozade range were affected.
Two years ago, 5m bottles of Lucozade were recalled after the Animal
Liberation Front said it had contaminated some of them. The scare turned out
to be a hoax.
</TEXT>
