<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Pressure over pit safety rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY backbenchers are putting pressure on the government over the new health
and safety regulations for the coal industry that come into force today.
In response to appeals from Nacods, the pit deputies' union, they are urging
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, to meet the concerns of miners over the
regulations. The rules separate the duties of pit inspection from
supervision - until now both carried out by Nacods, which is taking legal
action against the government over the changes.
Around 90 Conservative MPs have been approached by the union, including Mrs
Elizabeth Peacock, MP for Batley and Spen, and Mr Winston Churchill, MP for
Davyhulme, who both opposed the pit closure programme.
In letters to the backbenchers Mr Peter McNestry, Nacods' general secretary,
has warned that the new regulations eliminate 70 per cent of the safety
obligations enshrined in absolute statutory duties and replaced them with
more broadly defined duties and voluntary codes of conduct.
