FT  01 OCT 93 / World Trade News: Gephardt hopeful of changes to Nafta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONGRESSMAN Richard Gephardt, leader of the majority Democrats in the US
House of Representatives, has held out the possibility of measures that
would modify the North American Free Trade Agreement enough to bring him to
vote for it, writes George Graham in Washington.
Mr Gephardt last week announced that he would vote against Nafta as it
stood, since side agreements on environmental and labour issues negotiated
by President Bill Clinton still left it deficient.
However, Mr Gephardt said he was considering mechanisms to address his two
concerns about labour rights and wages in Mexico, and the financing of
environmental and infrastructure work along the US-Mexican border.
While President Carlos Salinas de Gortari of Mexico has promised an increase
in Mexico's minimum wage in line with productivity gains, Mr Gephardt said
he was looking at ways of tying wages to productivity.
For funding work along the Mexican border, Mr Gephardt said he favoured a
fee on any item that crossed the border in either direction.
