<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / World Bank to study Kenya aid squeeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORLD Bank last night announced it had agreed to chair a consultative
group meeting on Kenya in November, paving the way for an end to a two-year
aid squeeze.
In a statement last night the bank said that it was 'encouraged by the
substantial measures taken recently (by the government) and by its
commitment to continue these efforts'.
The statement followed talks this week with Kenyan officials in Washington.
Apart from steps to reduce mismanagement in the financial sector, the
measures include abolition of import licensing, curbs on money supply, moves
toward a market-driven exchange system, and reform of maize prices, said
officials of the bank.
The officials said they expected the government to complete the purge of the
banking sector while continuing to implement reforms in other sectors.
The decision marks a significant step in the return to international
respectability of President Daniel arap Moi, subjected to aid 'sanctions' in
November 1991 by donors angered by his government's economic mismanagement
and human rights abuses.
At the 1991 meeting of the consultative group in Paris, chaired by the bank,
donors announced that they were withholding their response to Kenya's
request for new assistance. Aid in the previous two years had been worth
some Dollars 1.4bn.
'Delegates made clear their willingness to support Kenya's economic
development, but stressed that levels of aid also depend on clear progress
in implementing economic and social reforms,' the donors said.
Within two weeks Mr Moi lifted the ban on multi-party politics. A general
election which followed a year later saw Mr Moi returned to power amid
opposition allegations of rigging.
In the 12 months since then Mr Moi's new cabinet has turned its attention to
a growing economic crisis, its efforts reinforced by the damaging shortfall
in vital aid flows.
</TEXT>
