<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / UN warns of aid calamity for Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, LAURA SILBER and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BELGRADE, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIA is 'looking into the jaws' of a humanitarian disaster this winter,
the United Nations said yesterday, warning that its aid operation for the
former Yugoslavia faced a cash shortfall of more than 50 per cent.
The warning comes amid fears that the Bosnian parliament's virtual rejection
of the peace proposals on Wednesday will set off further fighting across the
region.
In an effort to salvage the peace process, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald
Stoltenberg, the international mediators, yesterday met in Geneva and spoke
to Bosnian, US and UN representatives.
The Bosnian parliament has said it will accept the peace deal, which would
turn Bosnia into a loose union of three ethnic mini-states, only if land
seized by force is returned.
Diplomats warned that it was uncertain whether the mediators could produce
fresh diplomatic initiatives rapidly. The reponse from the Serb and Croat
leaders remained unclear.
Although UN sanctions against Serbia have left the Serb leaders in Belgrade
keen for a settlement, the Serbs have insisted they will not yield any more
land.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader, said the Serbs would continue to
build their state. He accused the Bosnian Moslems of seeking to stall the
process.
As tensions rose across Bosnia, Gen Rasim Delic, commander of the
Moslem-dominated Bosnian army, yesterday said he had ordered his troops to
cease military actions against the Croats.
Most ceasefires to date in Bosnia have broken down rapidly, and some
observers suggested that the move might have been prompted by fears of a
renewed Serb assault.
As Serb forces renewed their sporadic shelling of Sarajevo, Gen Delic warned
that Serb forces were massing in northern and eastern Bosnia.
Meanwhile, the Bosnian government also appeared to be under fresh attack
from its own people, after thousands of Bosnian Moslems had taken to the
streets in the north-western enclave of Bihac to protest against a military
crackdown ordered by Bosnian President Alia Izetbegovic after Mr Fikret
Abdic, Bihac's leader and Mr Izetbegovic's rival, declared the enclave
autonomous.
Bosnian troops were reported to be advancing on the town of Cazin, where
civilians had seized the local radio station in a gesture of defiance
against Mr Izetbegovic.
Yugoslavia today will strike six zeros from its dinar notes because of
soaring inflation. After the redenomination, 1m dinars will be equivalent to
one dinar. One kilogramme of meat yesterday cost 20bn dinars (DM10 or Pounds
4.10).
</TEXT>
