<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / UN aid routes to Bosnia-Hercegovina
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SARAJEVO
Requiring food aid: 380,000. Being delivered: 78%
Most of Sarajevo's food aid has got through in recent months, but the city
is critically short of fuel: 85 per cent of the population depends on
nautral gas, and the city's water pumps depend on electricity.
SOUTHERN BOSNIA AND HERCEGOVINA
Requiring food aid: 335,000; being delivered: 21%
The situation here is criitical, aid agencies say, with fighting between
Moslem and Croat forces blocking most deliveries. The Split warehouse has
stockpiled food, but agencies warn of disaster in cities like Mostar if
fighting continues.
CENTRAL BOSNIA AND TUZLA
Requiring food aid: 740,000; being delivered: 48%
The Tuzla region is relatively stable, but there is strong concern about
Tesanj and Maglaj, where up to 150,000 Moslems have been cut by Serb forces.
Clashes between Moslem and Croat forces have also isolated many communities,
with critical situations reported in Jablanica, Zenica, Vitez and Vares.
EASTERN BOSNIA
Requiring food aid: 336,000; being delivered: 69%
A considerable proportion of the aid supplied from Belgrade is getting
through. However, clashes between Moslem and Serb forces around the Moslem
enclaves of Zepa, Goradze and Srebrenica have blocked some convoys, and all
these towns are seriously overcrowded with refugees, with the water supply
in Srebrenica reportedly serious.
BANJA LUKA AND BIHAC
Requiring food aid: 489,000; being delivered: 78%
The situation is relatively stable, with most food aid supplied from Zagreb
reacing the area. Concern remains, however, about continuing harrasment of
the Moslem population in Serb-held Banja Luka and the presence of a large
refugee population.
