<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Gummer advocates one-tier local government structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND'S two-tier local government structure should be replaced with a
series of unitary authorities, even if it costs more than the present
system, Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, announced yesterday.
He also said that the Local Government Commission for England would complete
its work next year, having previously been due to finish in 1997. The
commission, chaired by Sir John Banham, former director-general of the
Confederation of British Industry, has already recommended the abolition of
three county councils.
Mr Gummer said he wanted unitary authorities because 'it's much clearer
where the responsibility lies'.
The measures alarmed business leaders and led to angry opposition from
county councils, which said transition costs might reach more than Pounds
1bn. Ernst &amp; Young, the accountants used by the commission, produced figures
suggesting that the transition costs for small unitary authorities might be
prohibitive.
District councils, which have campaigned for unitary - or single-tier -
authorities on existing boundaries, reacted positively.
Mr Gummer announced the shift by changing the policy guidance to the
commission, with the effect that: Retaining the existing two-tier structure
is now expected to be 'the exception'. 'Local consensus' is now important,
and the commission is to give 'particular weight' to proposals jointly put
forward by groups of authorities.
The importance of cost has been downgraded and the commission is not now
'precluded from recommending an option which would be marginally more
expensive than the status quo'.
'Very large' unitary authorities will need 'special justification in terms
of community identity'. Statutory and voluntary joint arrangements between
authorities can now be recommended for strategic planning.
The CBI welcomed the 'shorter period of uncertainty', but described the
revised guidance as 'fuzzy'. It said local businesses had consistently put
cost and quality of local services at the top of their list.
Mrs Josie Farrington, deputy chairman of the Association of County Councils
said: 'The case for changing local-government structure has yet to be made.
The proposals assume it has.'
But the Association of District Councils was 'delighted'. Mr Geoffrey
Filkin, chief executive, said very few districts would now ask for unitary
status without arranging mergers with other districts.
</TEXT>
