<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Firefighters near to deal around 1.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SETTLEMENT of the threatened dispute in Britain's fire services is likely
today when local-authority employers are expected to agree to honour the
firefighters' pay formula in full.
'We are on the verge of a deal', Mr Ken Cameron, Fire Brigades union general
secretary, said yesterday.
The pay increase that firefighters can expect next month may turn out to be
less than the government's 1.5 per cent public-sector pay limit for this
year, but Mr Cameron insisted that the union's fight was to preserve the
formula.
An official for local-authority employers said the firefighters' pay rise
would amount to between 1 per cent and 2 per cent.
The firefighters' 15-year-old pay formula links their earnings to that of
the upper quartile of male manual workers, based on the government's annual
New Earnings Survey, which was published yesterday.
The survey, a snapshot of the change in earnings for the year to April,
showed a 2.3 per cent rise for the upper quartile of male manual workers.
The average pay increase for all employees was 4 per cent and average gross
weekly earnings for full-time employees Pounds 317. Non-manual pay was
rising nearly twice as fast as manual pay and women's pay was rising faster
than men's.
The firefighters' pay formula requires that the April figure should be
adjusted to take into account earnings movements in the subsequent seven
months to November, as well as an annual survey of firefighters' earnings.
An official for the employers said yesterday it was 'good news' that the
relevant official earnings figure was so close to the government's 1.5 per
cent public-service pay limit.
The pay survey also shows that in the year to April 1993, public-sector pay
rose at 4.3 per cent compared with 4 per cent in the private sector.
Average gross weekly pay in the public sector was Pounds 321, compared with
Pounds 315.30 in the private sector. That is partly because there is a
higher proportion of managers and professionals in the public sector.
Medical practitioners averaging Pounds 736 a week were displaced from the
top of the earnings table by treasurers and company financial managers on
Pounds 746. The median level of earnings was Pounds 273 a week and the
bottom 10 per cent of employees earned less than Pounds 153 a week. The top
10 per cent earned more than Pounds 510.
Pay rises higher in the public sector, Page 12
</TEXT>
<XX>
